{
  "doc_id": "10229",
  "text": "EVs are widely involved in the transfer of infectious agents [CITATION_1] since they transfer viruses' receptors, that are essential for infection and survival in the infected cells, and also because of their action as potential decoys to elude the immune system [CITATION_2] . The role of EVs in the immune system modulation has been particularly studied in cancer, since tumor exosomal compartment is able to evade immune system by cell killing at a distance [CITATION_3] . Fas ligand (FasL) is present in EVs of melanoma cells [CITATION_4] , prostate cancer cells [CITATION_5] and in epithelial ovarian cancer cells. Moreover, they are all capable of inducing T-cell apoptosis [CITATION_6] . Indeed, Kim et al. [CITATION_7] also demonstrated that FasL-exposing EVs from sera of patients with oral squamous cell carcinoma induce T-cell apoptosis.",
